<div id="review_4032692123" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4032692123" />
    <a title="J.K. Grice" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/72137025-j-k-grice"><img alt="J.K. Grice" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1507324623p2/72137025.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4032692123?book_show_action=true">Jun 14, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="J.K. Grice" class="user" itemprop="url" name="J.K. Grice" href="/user/show/72137025-j-k-grice">J.K. Grice</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780312550677" href="/book/show/9897624-summer-of-night">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/72137025-j-k-grice?shelf=horror">horror</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4032692123" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8093143093693090558">How wonderful to return to the summer of 1960 in Elm Haven, Illinois. It was my third time sharing the adventures of Dale, Mike, Lawrence (don&apos;t call me Larry), Jim Harlen, Kevin, Duane, and Cordie Cooke. This book is like a dear old friend and you never tire of its company. Probably too shamelessly nostalgic, but that&apos;s part of Dan Simmon&apos;s magic, at least to this reader. Juxtaposed with the sweet small town flavor of SUMMER OF NIGHT is the horror story; one of the finest I&apos;ve ever read. This n</span>
  <span id="freeText8093143093693090558" style="display:none">How wonderful to return to the summer of 1960 in Elm Haven, Illinois. It was my third time sharing the adventures of Dale, Mike, Lawrence (don't call me Larry), Jim Harlen, Kevin, Duane, and Cordie Cooke. This book is like a dear old friend and you never tire of its company. Probably too shamelessly nostalgic, but that's part of Dan Simmon's magic, at least to this reader. Juxtaposed with the sweet small town flavor of SUMMER OF NIGHT is the horror story; one of the finest I've ever read. This novel is truly, unequivocally, frightening and gruesome in its darker aspects. <br /><br />Circa summer of 1976..... Elm Springs, Iowa was the town of twelve hundred people where I grew up. Like the kids in SUMMER OF NIGHT, we had our version of the Bike Patrol and a nerdy town cop everybody called Barney. We even had a rendering plant south of town, where animal carcasses were processed into.... something. The huge lumbering vehicle that rolled through town transporting dead livestock and roadkill was dubbed "The Gut Truck" by us kids. You could smell the Gut Truck rolling along from many blocks away. We often hopped on our bikes and quickly pedaled in the opposite direction. <br /><br />On those muggy summer nights, my neighborhood friends and I were allowed to (and routinely did) stay out after dark. We played kick-the-can, Truth or Dare, and told ghost stories under the corner street light. We had a ball. No one ever wanted to go home, but 10-10:30 was the outer limits of our parent imposed curfew. I knew that if I made it home for a rerun of Gunsmoke or the start of Johnny Carson, I wouldn't get grounded. Some nights I watched reruns of my favorite show, THE NIGHTSTALKER with Darren McGavin as the intrepid monster hunting reporter, Carl Kolchak. I often imagined what it would be like to battle the creatures that Kolchak faced in every episode. Growing up in Elm Springs, my friends and I never had to face any real monsters like the kids in Elm Haven had to. So SUMMER OF NIGHT for me is like my own childhood and The Nightstalker all rolled into one. It doesn't get much better than that.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8093143093693090558" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


